OMI-GRAPH:
  The authoritative representation of all system state.

OMI:
  Experimental bootable graph-machine substrate. OMI begins as a flat memory
  image interpreted through graph rules and grows toward an OMI-LISP runtime.

BOM:
  Byte Order Mark used as a clock principle: each tick is an endian
  reinterpretation boundary.

BOM tick:
  One application of the BOM temporal operator. In Phase 1 this reverses the
  loaded byte array and advances the tick counter.

CONS:
  A stable adjacency binding between graph nodes.

CONS closure:
  Transitive closure of CONS bindings. Future region formation is expected to
  derive from this closure.

NULL field:
  Memory interpreted as graph nodes before stable adjacency emerges.

NULL collapse:
  Resolution outcome for an adjacency pair that contains a NULL node.

Transient:
  Resolution outcome for an adjacency pair that is neither NULL collapse nor
  stable CONS binding.

Polyform:
  A reversible external projection of graph state, such as Braille, Aegean, or
  mixed-base encoding.

RULES.omi:
  Normative constraint layer for OMI-GRAPH state transitions. It uses
  Datalog-like predicates and RFC2119-style modal operators.

MUST:
  Hard invariant. A graph state that violates a MUST rule is invalid.

MUST_NOT:
  Hard prohibition. A graph state that satisfies a MUST_NOT rule is invalid.

SHOULD:
  Soft constraint or optimization pressure. Exceptions are valid only when the
  implication is understood and intentionally accepted.

MAY:
  Permitted extension point. A MAY rule does not create a validity requirement.

OPTIONAL:
  Implementation choice with no validity penalty.

Region:
  A graph component derived from CONS closure. Regions are future runtime
  objects and are not yet implemented in Phase 1.

SID:
  Stable identifier promoted from an OID after sufficient region stability.

OID:
  Observed identifier that has not yet reached stable semantic closure.

Projection:
  External view of graph state. A projection may encode or display OMI-GRAPH
  but must not become the source of graph truth.

Replay:
  Host-side recomputation of graph evolution from an image and rule version.

Multiboot2:
  Boot protocol used by GRUB to load the current OMI kernel and graph image
  module.
